children.name: Object

children.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all [Object]s is to return true if and
only if [:this:] and [other] are the same object.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override
the [hashCode] method as well to maintain consistency.

children.name: toString
children.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

children.name: noSuchMethod
children.comment:
[noSuchMethod] is invoked when users invoke a non-existant method
on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the
invocation are passed to [noSuchMethod] in an [InvocationMirror].
If [noSuchMethod] returns a value, that value becomes the result of
the original invocation.

The default behavior of [noSuchMethod] is to throw a
[noSuchMethodError].

children.name: hashCode
children.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the
same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality
operator [:==:]. Other than that there are no guarantees about
the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and
there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides [hashCode] it should override the
equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

children.name: runtimeType
children.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

children.name: Object
children.comment:
Creates a new [Object] instance.

[Object] instances have no meaningful state, and are only useful
through their identity. An [Object] instance is equal to itself
only.
Everything in Dart is an [Object].

children.name: createFixture
children.comment:
Creates a fixture and attach it to this body. Use this function if you need

If the density is non-zero, this function automatically updates the mass
of the body.
Contacts are not created until the next time step.

parameters like friction, restitution, user data, or filtering.
If the density is non-zero, this function automatically updates the mass
of the body.

children.name: destroyFixture

destroys all contacts associated with this fixture. This will
automatically adjust the mass of the body if the body is dynamic and the
fixture has positive density.
All fixtures attached to a body are implicitly destroyed when the body is
destroyed.

children.name: applyForce

affect the angular velocity. This wakes up the body.

point
  the world position of the point of application.

children.name: applyTorque

without affecting the linear velocity of the center of mass.
This wakes up the body.

It also modifies the angular velocity if the point of application
is not at the center of mass. This wakes up the body.

impulse
  the world impulse vector, usually in N-seconds or kg-m/s.
point
  the world position of the point of application.

children.name: applyAngularImpulse

children.name: active=
children.comment:
Set the active state of the body. An inactive body is not
simulated and cannot be collided with or woken up.
If you pass a flag of true, all fixtures will be added to the
broad-phase.
If you pass a flag of false, all fixtures will be removed from
the broad-phase and all contacts will be destroyed.
Fixtures and joints are otherwise unaffected. You may continue
to create/destroy fixtures and joints on inactive bodies.
Fixtures on an inactive body are implicitly inactive and will
not participate in collisions, ray-casts, or queries.
Joints connected to an inactive body are implicitly inactive.
An inactive body is still owned by a World object and remains
in the body list.

children.comment:
Initialize the proxy using the given shape. The shape
must remain in scope while the proxy is in use.

children.name: getSupport
children.comment: Get the supporting vertex index in the given direction.

children.name: getSupportVertex
children.comment: Get the supporting vertex in the given direction.

children.name: DistanceProxy
children.comment: Constructs a new DistanceProxy.

children.name: computeDistance
children.comment:
Compute the closest points between two shapes. Supports any combination of:
CircleShape and PolygonShape. The simplex cache is input/output.
On the first call set SimplexCache.count to zero.

children.name: Distance._construct
children.comment:
Construct a new Distance object. For internal use only. Don't directly
invoke.
Returns true if this ContactID equals the given ContactID.

children.name: setFrom
children.comment: Sets this contactID to be equal to the given ContactID.

children.name: isEqual
children.comment: Returns true if this ContactID equals the given ContactID.

children.name: zero
children.comment: Zeroes out the data.

children.name: ContactID
children.comment: Constructs a new ContactID.

children.name: ContactID.copy
children.comment: Constructs a ContactID that is a copy of the given ContactID.

children.name: EdgeResults
children.comment: Class for returning edge results

children.name: ClipVertex
children.comment: Used for computing contact manifolds.

children.name: testOverlap
children.comment: Returns true if the two given shapes overlap.

children.name: getPointStates
children.comment:
Compute the point states given two manifolds. The states pertain to the
transition from manifold1 to manifold2. So state1 is either persist or
remove while state2 is either add or persist.

children.name: clipSegmentToLine
children.comment:
Clipping for contact manifolds.
Sutherland-Hodgman clipping.

children.name: collideCircles
children.comment: Compute the collision manifold between two circles.

children.name: collidePolygonAndCircle
children.comment: Compute the collision manifold between a polygon and a circle.

children.name: edgeSeparation
children.comment:
Find the separation between poly1 and poly2 for a given edge normal on
poly1.

children.name: findMaxSeparation
children.comment:
Find the max separation between poly1 and poly2 using edge normals from
poly1.

children.name: collidePolygons
children.comment: Compute the collision manifold between two polygons.

children.name: Collision._construct
children.comment:
Constructs a new Collision object. Should only be constructed once (in the
pool). Retrieve from the pool to use.

children.name: setFromCombination
children.comment:
Sets this box to be a combination of the two given boxes.
The combination is determined by picking and choosing the lowest x and y
values from the lowerBounds to form a new lower bound and picking and
choosing the largest x and y values from the upperBounds to form a new
upperBound.

children.name: setBounds
children.comment: Sets the bounds to the given values.

children.name: testOverlap
children.comment: Returns true if the given box overlaps with this box.

children.name: isValid
children.comment:
Returns true if the lower bound is strictly less than the upper bound and
both bounds are themselves valid (Vector.isValid() returns true).

children.name: contains
children.comment: Returns true if this box contains the given box.

children.name: setFrom
children.comment: Sets this box to be a copy of the given box.

children.name: center
children.comment: Returns the center of this box.

children.name: AxisAlignedBox
children.comment:
Constructs a new box with the given lower and upper bounds. If no bounds
are specified, constructs the box with both bounds at the origin.

children.name: drawPolygon
children.comment: Draw a closed polygon provided in CCW order.

children.name: drawPoint
children.comment: Draws the given point with the given radius and color.

children.name: drawSolidPolygon
children.comment: Draw a solid closed polygon provided in CCW order.

children.name: drawCircle
children.comment: Draw a circle.

children.name: drawSolidCircle
children.comment: Draw a solid circle.

children.name: drawSegment
children.comment: Draw a line segment.

children.name: drawTransform
children.comment: Draw a transform.  Choose your own length scale.

children.name: drawString
children.comment: Draw a string.

children.name: setCamera
children.comment:
Sets the center of the viewport to the given x and y values and the
viewport scale to the given scale.

children.name: getScreenToWorldToOut
children.comment:
Screen coordinates are specified in argScreen. These coordinates are
converted to World coordinates and placed in the argWorld return vector.

children.name: getWorldToScreenToOut
children.comment:
World coordinates are specified in argWorld. These coordinates are
converted to screen coordinates and placed in the argScreen return vector.

children.name: reportFixture
children.comment:
Called for each fixture found in the query AABB.
return false to terminate the query.

children.name: shouldCollide
children.comment:
Return true if contact calculations should be performed between these two
shapes.

children.name: beginContact
children.comment: Called when two fixtures begin to touch.

children.name: endContact
children.comment: Called when two fixtures cease to touch.

children.name: preSolve
children.comment:
This is called after a contact is updated. This allows you to inspect a
contact before it goes to the solver. If you are careful, you can modify 
the contact manifold (e.g. disable contact).
A copy of the old manifold is provided so that you can detect changes.
Note: this is called only for awake bodies.
Note: this is called even when the number of contact points is zero.
Note: this is not called for sensors.
Note: if you set the number of contact points to zero, you will not
get an EndContact callback. However, you may get a BeginContact callback
the next step.
Note: the oldManifold parameter is pooled, so it will be the same object
for every callback for each thread.

children.name: postSolve
children.comment:
This lets you inspect a contact after the solver is finished. This is
useful for inspecting impulses.
Note: the contact manifold does not include time of impact impulses,
which can be arbitrarily large if the sub-step is small. Hence the impulse
is provided explicitly in a separate data structure.
Note: this is only called for contacts that are touching, solid, and awake.
